Reviewers' Comments to Author:

Reviewer: 1

Comments:
Dear Authors,

Thank you for your efforts.

I would like to add the following comments:

1. The field of sign language computing has evolved from fundamental Sign Language Recognition (SLR), which focused on translating gestures into text, toward Sign Language Production (SLP), where the goal is to generate human-like signing from linguistic inputs, to convince readers, it is nice to include some of the following research progress: “IDF-Sign: Addressing Inconsistent Depth Features for Dynamic Sign Word Recognition” and “FSign-Net: Depth Sensor Aggregated Frame-based Fourier Network for Sign Word Recognition”, "Spatial-temporal feature-based end-to-end Fourier network for 3D sign language recognition", "American sign language words recognition using spatio-temporal prosodic and angle features: A sequential learning approach", "Minimizing redundancy in hand dynamic features for enhanced sign language recognition",  to contextualize their limitations to the field and demonstrate that Text2Sign marks a critical shift toward synthesis, moving beyond 2D video to leverage 3D and depth modalities.

2. "Impractical for real-time" is a common claim, but "computationally efficient" is vague. Instead of just saying it's efficient, state what your model achieves on a specific Frames Per Second (FPS) on target edge hardware (like an NVIDIA Jetson or mobile SoC, etc.).

3. FVD (Fréchet Video Distance) is a standard metric, but it doesn't always correlate with human understanding of sign language.

4. Mention how the frozen CLIP encoder helps the model understand "unseen" text prompts that weren't in the training set.

5. Provide a table to compare your method directly with the best existing methods on the same datasets.

6. Highlights your limitations with respect to your claims.
7. Try to avoid unsubstantiated and over-exaggerated claims.

