Reviewer: 2

Comments:
- I think the “computationally efficient” claim is overstated: the model is extremely large (hundreds of millions of parameters) and the reported inference time is seconds per short clip on a data-center GPU, which is not compatible with real-time or edge deployment as currently demonstrated.

- I’m not convinced the evaluation targets the core goal of sign language generation. Current metrics (denoising MSE, FVD-like proxy, motion heuristics) do not measure linguistic correctness, intelligibility, or whether the generated signing matches the text meaning.

- I think the experimental evidence is underpowered for strong architectural conclusions. Several key ablations are trained for a very small number of optimization steps, so differences may reflect early-training dynamics rather than stable, fully-trained performance.

- I’m concerned the quality metrics are not reliable as reported. “FVD-proxy in pixel space” is not a standard or well-validated proxy for sign-language video quality, and computing generation metrics on only a handful of synthesized clips is too small to be convincing.

- I think the “frozen CLIP is better” conclusion is not fully justified without stronger controls. A randomly initialized custom text encoder trained from scratch under a short training budget is an unfair comparison; a fair baseline would use a pretrained text encoder of similar capacity or train the custom encoder longer with matched compute.

- I’m not convinced the factorized-attention story is settled. The paper compares factorized vs full 3D attention at one low resolution and short clip length; the trade-off may change at higher resolutions, longer temporal windows, and with realistic sampling step counts.

- I think the dataset split and generalization claims need tightening. Sign-language generation is highly signer-dependent; without a signer-disjoint split (or at least clear reporting of signer distribution and split protocol), it’s hard to trust “generalization” improvements.

- I’d like ablations that isolate conditioning: no-text conditioning, random text conditioning, and different text encoders (pretrained transformer-only, CLIP variants), to show the model is truly text-faithful rather than generating generic signing motion.

- Releasing the code would be beneficial for reproducibility.

