Reviewer: 3

Comments:
The paper proposes a Text2Sign language generation framework that integrates a frozen CLIP-based text encoder with a 3D UNet backbone augmented by Diffusion Transformer blocks employing factorized spatial and temporal attention.
The manuscript is concise, clearly written, and generally easy to follow. The topics of  sign language translation are timely and relevant. However, the following comments should be addressed:
1) The Abstract should be improved. Although the research topic involves several abbreviations (or acronyms), their use should be avoided in the Abstract whenever possible. In addition, the Abstract should clearly indicate the main contributions of the study as well as its limitations.
2) The methods are currently presented as a subsection of the ‘Introduction’. However, the methodology of a scientific study is sufficiently important to warrant a dedicated section rather than being included as a subsection. I therefore recommend creating a separate section entitled ‘Methods’ or ‘Methodology’ and expanding it to provide a clearer and more detailed description for readers interested in the technical aspects of the work.
3) Similar comments apply to the subsection titled ‘Related Work’. I recommend creating a separate section, for example, ‘Literature Review’. In addition, the literature review should be expanded, as several relevant and recent papers are currently missing, including (among others): a)  https://doi.org/10.3390/app9132683 ; b) https://doi.org/10.1007/s10209-021-00823-1 ; c) https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neucom.2025.130421; d) https://doi.org/10.1007/s10209-015-0413-4 ; e) https://doi.org/10.3389/feduc.2023.1121597 ; ...
4) It is important to compare the model with existing (or simiar) approaches developed by other researchers;
5) The authors have employed multi-metric evaluations, and the inclusion of a normalized multi-metric comparison is a notable strength of the study;
6) The writing quality should be polished and the manuscript structure requires refinement.

